With Bitcoin, you can pay and sell without banks.
The opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees among the parties involved.
In addition, as often in these technologies, political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, which was invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
Around 200,000 transactions have been recorded via 15,000 computers on the network.
Close to a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or payments.
The bitcoin exchange rate, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros), fell to 2 dollars five months later, returning to around dozen dollars (rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com site).
Nothing very impressive compared to global transactions in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took interest in it in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as 'credits', used to progress in a video game you play or which you can exchange for.
The social network Facebook has also developed this system.
However, on each occasion, a central authority monitors and handles the exchange.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both custodians of the account book, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does the network work?
The transaction between two users is actually carried out between two electronic addresses like with an email.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The set of information associated with this transaction is signed electronically by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The file is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins are kept in the public book of accounts, broadcast across the network.
Key step is entering the new transaction in the book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge issued to computers, and the winner, a kind of interim central bank, will have the privilege of adding this extra line.
This is a file hashing phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computer takes the new transaction and adds a number to it, then hash it all up.
The goal is to find the number that gives a special imprint (lots of zeros at the beginning).
After this number is found, other nodes can easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would alter the imprint.
If a user wanted to defraud by paying two times with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other would remain an orphan because the two have different imprints.
The computer that resolves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this award is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore restricted to 21 million, but they are divided down to the 100 millionth, leaving some margin...
The challenge is also enhanced with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stole.
The loophole used is not the protocol itself, says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also highlights the possibility of money laundering using this anonymous service.
Cash also has this weakness.
Major players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Other platforms, such as the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from Weizmann Institute in Israel, analysed the accounting books and found that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge selloffs" were launched.
"Three thousand dollars were exchanged" welcomes Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins to gold.
