Surprised everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text on the following day.
The Head of State gave the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
For two years Egypt has relied on a provisional text, changed several times, which has weakened institutions and led to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative only serves to enhance the divide in the country.
The President is persevering in his "autocratic delirium," continuing to "back on his word" and "trampal the law."
The advocates believe that this is the quickest way to end the institutional and political crisis, by speeding the transition process.
A referendum is due to be held within two weeks.
The Brothers have a short period of time, which forces them to abandon their plan to explain the text, article by article, to Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to achieve popular and democratic legitimacy while the dispute rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be confident that Egyptians will vote favorably, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
