The strange atmosphere that 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, with large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals were missing.
In mid November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling they had failed to assert their views.
Human rights, minority groups or civil society have done similarly.
In order to obtain a quorum, 11 alternates were added yesterday morning.
Some are close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
The articles were mostly unanimely voted.
They also marveled at one of the only diversions of the day, which was a reflection of the Constituent Assembly clock.
The text, which is still being voted on yesterday evening, has 234 articles.
The main focus of attention, article 2, remains in the final analysis identical to the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which Islamic law is a major claim, wanted to replace "the principles" with "the rules," which would have allowed stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article was not changed is a guarantee of goodwill and respect for other elements of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy" responds the liberals, who see only communication coup.
Because in their opinion Islamisation of the Constitution is done through other articles.
The latter refers to article 220, which grants Al-Azhar University an advisory role, with particular reference to verifying the conformity of the laws with sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is a serious concern because the people called on to advise are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This suggests the beginnings of a theocracy.
The liberals' fears are also fueled by the fact that the next Rector of the university will likely be much less moderate than the current one.
"For time being, there is no concrete religious implication.
