In Israel, Holy places are waiting for Ukrainian tourists, the omphalos and a saline water sea.
The Holy Land combines the splendor of biblical truths, modern comfort and prime nature.
AIF [Facts and Fact] newspaper highlighted the five most important reasons why it is a must to visit Israel.
Please celebrate the sacred places.
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is considered that all who enter this baptism "bath" are blessed by God.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his magic: turned water into wine at a wedding, walked on water, calmed a storm, and filled the nets.
This is also where Jesus appeared before his disciples and after his resurrection.
The most important number of Holy places is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk through the Grief or Dolorosa Way.
The journey starts from the Antonia Fortress - Praetorium - where the judgement occurred, and continues through the Old Town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha - the place of the crucifixion, Stone of Unction and place of Jesus' death.
This is also the location of the symbolic Christian omphalos, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem is built on the site where the tree used to make the cross for Jesus' crucifixion.
The most sacred places for Jews are the Wailing Wall, which is the only surviving part of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes here with their wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Travel along a vertical axis
Massada Fortress is a secret retreat from enemies, built by Herod in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on cliffs in the mountain range at an elevation of 450 m above sea level.
They can be reached on foot only by those who are into mountain climbing.
Others are transported to this historical mountaintop by a cableway.
In the north of the country, at an elevation of 1600-2040 m, there is a famous ski resort called Hermon, which is filled with tourists in winter months.
The bus brings people to it from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of ski pistes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods used to live on the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country has about 300 museums.
You cannot visit all of them on one trip.
The five most interesting ones are worth a visit.
The Museum of Israel is located close to Knesset (Parliament).
It has ancient Qumran manuscripts and Dead Sea scrolls found in the caves of the Judean desert, along with about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artefacts.
The Art Museum in Tel Aviv is also interesting.
The exhibits include a wide range of impressionists and expressionists like Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Sisley, Cezanne, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the bath museum Al Basha, which is a collection of ancient Turkish baths with models of visitors and bath attendants of the time.
In Caesarea, you can visit the private Ralli Museum, where you can enjoy the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no tour guides or gift shops.
Entry is free, and contributions are strictly prohibited.
The fifth is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel-Aviv, which tells one of the most dramatic stories in history.
The most tragic section is the children's memorial, built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go in and find yourself in complete darkness.
Stars are glimmering, sparkles.
Listen to names of Jewish children and countries where they die.
Ukraine is mentioned in the article too.
Wellness
There are three resort areas in Israel, located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea.
Each have swimming pools, aquaparks, dolphinaria and oceanaria.
The remarkable fact is that one can swim in the Red Sea even in winter months, because water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air warms to 23 degrees.
Dead Sea is even warmer, and people swim in it all year round.
Incidentally, it is the most unusual sea in the world, located in the lowest point of the planet - 417 m below sea level.
The azure water is saline and easily keeps you afloat, even if you do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are surreal in their beauty.
People come here to undergo a treatment course with salt water - wraps and medicinal muds, and to improve their health if they have dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, or diabetes.
Touch the secrets of antiquity
The remains are conserved in the old section of Tel-Aviv - in the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean Sea.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, and Mesopotamia runs through it.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
The legend says that this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beauty Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists really like to walk the narrow streets named after Zodiac sign.
They say, if you touch the wall on the street of your sign, fortune will come to you.
In Jaffa you can meet new brides from all over Israel and even from other countries for photo sessions.
In Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can walk around a Roman theater, "capture" the Crusader fortress.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman commanders, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourist note
If you go to Israel, do not worry about your poor English knowledge.
For the trip, it is better to take dollars, not euros, because they are easy to exchange for shekels (currently 1 dollar = 3.8 shekels).
Cities are mainly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram, and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, comprising six stops and connecting upper town with lower town.
In essence, it is an underground cable railway.
A ticket for any type of city transport costs 6 shekels, and you can ride for 1.5 hours with transfers.
According to Jewish tradition, Sabbath is celebrated in Israel.
The following Friday evening and sunset on Saturday, markets, stores, and public transport stop working.
The work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels have only kosher food, with no meat, fish, fish with no scales or foods that mix milk with meat.
The wide range of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts cooked with coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus paste, various sauces, falafel (balls made of ground chickpeas), fruit and vegetables.
The street in Israel is not full of homeless dogs.
There are many well fed cats, which walk around lazily.
In the evening, they can even sleep on the roofs of parked cars.
This pussycat likes busy places and does not refuse treats.
Cheap car rental, depending on the type, costs from 37 (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) dollars a day.
Plus insurance of 15 dollars a day.
Bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Museum entrance costs 30 shekels on average.
In numbers
In 2012, over three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Visitors and holidaymakers mostly arrive from USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, and Ukraine.
January and October 2012 118,800 Ukrainian tourists visited the Holy Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the removal of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
Only the high and mighty get to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While deputies and human rights activists argue about the purpose of mandatory language testing, the country already has scam artists who sell fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russia cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support families back home.
New law was implemented on December 1, which requires every migrant worker to pass a Russian language test.
The law is currently only applicable to those who intend to work in services, housing and utility services, household services, and retail.
With time - as promised by the Federal Migration Service - tests will be mandatory for all non-residents.
In addition to language, Russian history and basic legal system will be tested.
Language knowledge will be confirmed both to receive and extend the work permit.
An exception is effective only for citizens of countries where Russian is a state language.
People who received education certificates and diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also exempted under the law.
Purpose, doom, and protection of rights
Seven testing points will be operating under the supervision of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, People‚Äôs Friendship University of Russia, Moscow State University (MGU), and other Russian education institutions.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 such centres have been opened.
The initiative to introducing the testing was supported by State Duma members and the Federal Migration Services.
Human rights activists, repeatedly asked in the press before the law came into force: what will it actually achieve?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and for non-residents?
First of all, according to representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from labour slavery.
Many people are talking about protection of work migrant rights, explains the Head of the Representative Office of the Federal Migration Services of Russia, Viktor Sebelev.
Rights protection should begin before they depart.
Only organized selection will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without profession, education, who do not know Russian, who do not have a medical certificate start to have problems.
If a migrant does not understand the language, he is doomed to meet unconscious people who, pretending to help, will force him to a "ticket" to a huge, cramped barracks where many others like him will suffer without food and documents.
We receive many complaints from our migrant migrants.
They are promised one thing at home, but when they arrive, they are lied to, their passports are taken, they are not paid what they were promised.
Not be angry, boss!
However, many Central Asian citizens who plan to work in Russia admit that not only their understanding of the language of the country they are going to work is poor, but they can barely write in their own language.
However, this is not so much their fault, but due to poverty: very few Turks, Uzbeks, and Tajiks can even access basic education.
Their families do not have food to feed their children, not even enough clothing, shoes, and supplies.
After reaching adolescence, these kids go to work at the first opportunity.
It is hard, if language knowledge is poor, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Human rights activists note one important point about language law.
Testing will be conducted only for migrants with legal status.
If they have no status, no testing or official work will be done in the future.
In the meantime most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or No Unauthorized Entry"
Many foreigners claim that official status in our country is not that easy.
The reason lies in bureaucratic hurdles and the already mentioned language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12,000 to 16,000 rubles.
Whereas a fake registration is done quickly and costs only one and half thousand.
The Russian Police know that we mainly have fake papers, without registration, therefore the extortion.
They ask for hundred or two for cigarettes, tea, according to journalists.
"Roll up, not be cheap, get your art"
The first day of the law's entry into force, it turned out that not only migrant registration documents can be fake.
A few forged certificates about passing language tests have been seized by Federal Migration Services officers already.
Forged documents are printed on a standard colour printer.
The boxes were not free for their owner: each migrant who wanted to facilitate the task of passing the tests paid seven thousand rubles for them.
It is two and half times more than the official testing process, which costs three thousand.
Officials and human rights activists agree that the main goal in the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be just bought.
The authorities are able to offer time to complete a basic language course.
In addition, those who do not have Russian language knowledge will be offered work in areas that do not require active communication with people.
