"At the moment, the mind cannot be too well deceived"
Among modern technology fans a popular topic is augmented reality, which is now seen mainly through special glasses.
First, a functional model was shown by Google in summer, at its annual conference. Then in November Microsoft filed an application for patent.
However, according to the conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technology group in Microsoft Cambridge laboratory, Shahram Izadi, glasses are a thing of past for Microsoft scientists.
Their interest is in manipulating virtual objects in air with bare hands, creating virtual open spaces.
- Please tell us in simple terms about your research group.
- We work on the interaction of people with machines, at the same time trying to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
While people generally are stuck with working with pixels on a flat screen and sometimes pointing finger at them.
We want to look 5-10 years into the future and predict cardinal changes in this interaction.
Xbox and Kinect sensors are a step forward. Almost no Xbox is sold without Kinect today, because everyone likes to control by gestures.
- What else is awaits us in the future?
- Despite the fact that Kinect shifted the interaction to the physical level, much still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information entry has improved (the system receives more data), but output still needs to improve.
We are trying to change this, working on truly three-dimensional display systems using various technologies, including projection technologies.
We need to let the computer world into our physical world, make it more tangible.
This is why we need to identify both the user and the space around him.
Then we will be able to supplement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
Above all, get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It is popular, but is it over-estimated?
- It clearly cannot be called a cure-for-all, but privacy is a concern, because we do not always want to tell others about our actions and intentions.
All types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
Examples are a project to control devices in public places, which was focused on movements, not wide movements but small, reserved ones.
Movements were not recorded by a camera, but by a hand bracelet that determined the movement of bones and muscles.
It is huge right now, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a hand watch.
In general, the future lies in the mix control, e.g. movement + voice.
What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to give you this bottle of water?
You will talk and show at the same time.
- Usually I just say.
- It will be very difficult to detect.
- So you want to make users adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at that moment?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approximation.
In the near future, we will mainly work on developing new sensors that will allow more precise determination of a person's reaction.
This could be, e.g. laser sensors. They have a good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Not enough resolution, depth or something else?
- Generally, the current generation is what we can base ourselves on in working on three-dimensional recognition.
Then, it would be good to have eight mega pixels with 1000 k/s speed.
It is not only the mega pixels, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From the latter perspective, all current technologies are not good enough for us - this adds work to the algorithm designers.
The resolution on the X, Y, and Z axis is important.
Speed, number of images per second, is also important.
Human movements are relatively dynamic, and current 30 k/s is really not enough for gestures.
Steven Bathiche from our Redmond laboratory created a touch sensor with a regulated processing delay from 1 to 100 ms, while modern serial sensors are closer to the latter indicator (60-100).
No one knows how this affects the interaction between man and machine.
In my work, it would be very helpful to have a device that does not require touching and would have more images per second.
- Do the number of cameras need to be increased?
- In Kinect there are three cameras now, one being an infrared emitter and the second one, the receiver of the signal.
The third one is actually a regular sensor of visible range.
It is not used to determine the object's depth.
Potentially, a large number of cameras could solve the problem...
However, it can be worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analogue Kinect, play with the flexion of camera position and see how this will help in three-dimensional determination of the position.
- As far as I know, Microsoft has not presented its glasses to the public, unlike Google.
What do you think is the most promising platform for the daily use of augmented reality technologies?
- It is not very convenient to walk around with a smart phone in your hands all the time, but I think that the coolest option is transitional augmented reality, where you can shift from glasses to smart phone, projection display, and everything else based on a cloud platform.
glasses are very personal devices, which is their strength (private things are only seen by you) and, at the same time, their weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects with other people.
- Imagine for a minute that manipulating virtual hologramic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from Ironman but to a regular person.
The problem with this idea is that the critics often point out: no tactile feedback!
Hands feel nothing!
What answers do you have prepared for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive attempt at the interaction between man and machine.
The eighth will probably be the addition of tactile sensations.
The most interesting trick is to use the second hand as a sort of matrix for the image.
It is great at registering pushes!
The technology is really aimed at giving these "images in the air" a sense of tangibility, for example, the interference of several targeted ultrasound rays in the specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation, but very weak now, as if someone blew your fingertip.
Bracelets that affect the nerve endings in fingertips are also a good area.
- Have you try to deceive the mind?
To force it to think that it feels something that it should feel when it sees something?
- This is a good idea and we have not tried it yet.
The challenge is one that will not be solved so quickly - how to force a person who is physically in a very limited space to believe that he is walking along an open, almost limitless space. We are working on treadmills (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms, and giant balloons.
So far deceiving the mind has had limited success, but there is work for many years to come.
The reason why virtual reality is so attractive to researchers is that many things are in their very beginnings.
