NKU Head: Svarc System audit has failed because of politicians.
The Czech Republic has sound control bodies and good legal standards when it comes to public contracts, but it lags behind in its application.
This was told by Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office (NKU) in an interview for Aktualne.cz.
The Law will never be perfect, but its application should be just - this is what we are missing in the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also reached by the joint audit from Czech and German auditors.
As an example of improper practice, they cite Petr Necas' approach to the so-called "Svarc System."
The Prime Minister recently claimed that the ODS will not be burdening business owners with its checks - so is it forbidden or allowed?
The Law must be set out one way or another and if it prohibits something, even the Head of the Government cannot prevent the work of its department, which is duty-bound to monitor and enforce it.
At the audit committee's meeting in the House of Deputies you spoke about a joint project between Czech Republic and Germany, within which public contract legislation was compared.
What exactly was this about?
This is about parallel auditing, which we started around two years ago.
This is about how European legislation governs the handling of public contracts, followed by individual state legislations and then the actual practice.
The audit is still in progress, and although the audit is yet to be complete, some interesting differences have become apparent - in general terms, our legislation may be even more concise and complete, but the practice is in some aspects better in Germany.
This confirms that creating more concise rules is not enough, and that attention must be paid to the actual application of these laws.
What does this project actually help you with, and what do you think its outcome will bring?
This kind of joint audit could help to curtail efforts to specify our law, to reduce and perfect boundaries, when it does not have such positive impact.
Economy is acquiring the required thing at a reasonable (which is not always the lowest) price, so that profiteering and possible criminal proceedings may be prevented.
However, just because we have reduced the order limits does not mean something will be acquired.
The system may get overloaded with paperwork, and those who wish to look for loopholes in it will be able to take advantage of it far more easily than if the limits were kept higher.
This is domestic problems about the practical application of public contract legislation.
How does the audit system work in Germany?
There is an office like the NKU, or is it differently organized?
The office functions like our NKU, and it has a committee although it is appointed slightly differently.
Strengths are also similar to degree, though Germany is federally organized, so the auditor courts are also at the Member State level - in this respect they may differ from our own.
The BRH can only audit federal money, known to us as state funds.
Public funds, which for us are administered by regional and municipal authorities, are audited by the federal courts of auditors there.
If they have a more straightforward legislation, is it more straightforward than ours?
Overall, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data, but it cannot be said that Germany is better in every aspect.
It may be because they have better enforcement?
It is certainly not true, but I prefer not to make such comparisons.
It should be added that even in an exemplary country, they face a whole range of problems.
If that were not the case, they would not gain anything from working with our office, would they?
Looking back to domestic legislation, what did the amendment to public contracts legislation mean for your office, and is it already felt?
The period since the amendment came into force has been quite short, so it has not manifested in our audit work yet.
Since we conduct our audits post-mortem, a certain delay is taken into account.
The changes have only been observed in the preparedness process for future audits - we have launched our new "fiscal failure risk detection" system, with which we have processed over 14 000 public contracts and these have been analysed - that is where changes will clearly appear, because of the changed limits, the changed conditions governing selection processes, and so on.
The benefits of this legislation are either a benefit or a burden on the bureaucratic system?
I believe this legislation is a step in the right direction, and I hope this will be confirmed.
The problem, which may arise here, is that the law becomes too restricted and will not be enforceable.
In previous rules, auditing parties were already bound by their audit provider (e.g. in regional operational programmes, the regional office) to the fact that every infringement of public contracts law means a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth restricting the law in that case?
I do not think this is the way.
The system should prevent those who want to attack and abuse it, but not penalize those who make a mistake on a technicality that does not affect the final decision.
This kind of system will only increase pressure on bureaucracy.
How can we get out of this?
Then lets see where this dead end takes us.
The Prime Minister recently announced that the ODS will not be burdened by the so-called "Svarc System" - what does this mean?
Is the Svarc System prohibited or allowed?
The Law must be set out one way or another, and if it prohibits something, even the Head of the Government cannot prevent the work of its department, which is duty-bound to monitor and enforce.
The lawyer may say: "Let us change this law and relax it," but he cannot say we should pretend it is not there.
The law on public contracts has relatively strict rules about the formalities which must be followed - which is the right way to protect public tenders.
The other hand, it is a tragedy when the best offer is excluded on a technicality.
The Law will never be perfect, but its application should be just - this is what we are missing.
