The B√ºcherberg was awarded second place in the "Best Library of NL 2012" competition.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the National Wood Award 2012.
The faceless small-town retort, that until now had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and a stunningly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would expect to find dairy plant, has been enhanced by a modern piece of architecture.
First and first of all, Spijkenisse now has its first public cultural building in its history.
The long journey to the book
First impression: the Eldorado of books under a cheese dome.
There is a lift that climbs through the centre of the mountain massif, but the true joys of space and literature are revealed when footsteps are taken.
The interior space, glazed throughout, is bright and open, the fired clinker floors and the elegant street lights speak the unmistakable language of a public square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for a park bench, a dog, and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere there are books, books, books.
Traditionally book shelves run along the facade, and in the centre there is a large, dark space, which is usually unpleasant and impersonal.
We turned the classical spatial configuration on its head and turned the reading area inside out.
The interior of the B√ºcherberg is very well used: in the centre there are offices, Internet library, chess club, an environment centre and the central technical support room.
