Architects and construction engineers often shake heads at the unknown construction materials.
‚ÄùHere we wanted to work with recyclable materials,‚Äù explained Joop Trouborst, Project Manager for Spijkenisse, on request of the Standard.
Then one day we found a suitable waste product for agriculture, on a Frisian farm.
Many years, millimetre-thick artificial fabric has been used in greenhouses and fields in Netherlands as a base layer.
It is cheap and saves time.
The thin textile lasts for two seasons and is then disposed of as bulk waste.
For the library, the fabric was - for the first time in these quantities - pressed into four-centimetre-thick boards.
Under heat, the so-called Landbouw plastic (KLP) changes colour to a dark, homogenous and robust material that smells like a mix of new car smell and trainers.
