Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
In the vote on the integration of Palestine, Germany abstained from voting.
Stephen Szabo, Expert in US-European relations, says that Berlin is walking a thin diplomatic line.
Deutsche Welle:
Berlin later abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, due to their special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
It is not believed to support the American position either.
Germany wanted to show its independence - albeit without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting, when it came to setting up a no-fly zone.
This was ultimately implemented by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to adopt a clear position when it comes to important international affairs?
Yes, it does.
It has just reorganised its foreign policy, indeed moving away from a policy that was, so called, managed by the USA, in favour of a German foreign policy.
This situation is further agraved by the fact that the Europeans do not have a coherent and standardised policy.
The Germans thus find themselves caught between two fronts.
It is expected of them to play a more independent role, but this is something they do not usually do.
I believe that they are still finding their way in this role, but they are moving to a more normal foreign policy.
A similar foreign policy to that of France, or Great Britain.
What specifically does a "normal" foreign policy entail, from a German perspective?
It shows a willingness to adopt international positions, independent of the USA or European partners.
The German foreign policy is based on economic policy, that is, by export and its relations with specific regions such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other major powers and Germany must protect its interests.
These economic interests have influenced their attitude to the Middle East conflict and their participation in the UN?
On the other hand, Germany has major revenue markets in the Middle East, and particularly in the Gulf States.
It is therefore important not to affront the public but also the elite in the Arab countries.
In any case, this plays a role.
However, I would not want to ascribe too much weight to this.
It does play a key role in Germany's considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the USA by refusing to vote on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe and even in the USA, a great understanding for the German position is growing.
It is not believed to be as dramatic as was the case in Libya.
Maybe it will even earn Germany some respect.
After all, it signals that the country must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
In Europe there are diverse opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
The USA have a clear message in support of a veto.
There are differences between the USA and many European countries?
The American domestic policy has always been a barrier to these differences.
I think that secretly, the government under Obama actually has a great deal of understanding for the European situation.
However, due to the political situation here, the government is naturally unable to voice this position publicly.
It is my belief that the actual differences in opinion are not so wide as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanjahu, Obama is really not so enthused by Netanjahu's policy.
How can Germany reconcile its close relations with Israel and the USA on one hand, and the position of its most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that this is precisely what makes things so difficult for the Germans.
It would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and standardised European policy, which is currently not the case.
They are unable to be part of a wider authority and must instead drive matters forward from their own position.
This is exactly what they are doing with the Euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a key role in leading Europe towards a standardised European position.
This is a difficult task for Germany, given its relations with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
It is a clear understanding that Germany must play a more independent role.
Does Germany view itself as an important international player - does Germany actually want to play a lead role?
Does Germany still find leadership roles difficult?
Germany is still not used to it, the country continues to be uncomfortable and for obvious reasons, is still unable to play a more prominent role.
If we look at the Euro crisis, every time Germany takes a more prominent role, various anti-German feelings appear.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is actually the same old problem: one does not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this position, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to the most diverse of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
The USA‚Äôs influence on European politics is continually declining, but the EU is currently not feeling this gap.
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
If they do not like it, even if it is uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - life is!
Stephen Szabo is Associate Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and political experts from Europe and North America meet to research the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, which has specialised in German policy, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
