What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhoea.
HIV, human papilloma viruses, genital herpes and hepatitis are common STIs.
Crabs and scabies are parasitic STIs.
Who are main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhoea occur mainly in men who have sexual intercourse with other men.
Robert Koch Institute believes that at least four in five of all syphilis cases in Germany are transmitted by sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis, gonorrhoea and human papilloma viruses are frequent sexually transmitted diseases.
The HIV spread among heterosexual adults in this country is relatively low, but around 20 percent of newly acquired HIV cases occur in this group.
among young people chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country human papilloma viruses are also frequently found in young people.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are not identifiable.
Robert Koch Institute reports that syphilis infections have gone up from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of newly contracted HIV cases has declined since 2007.
In 2011 there were around 2,700 cases.
This is around one tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate sexually transmitted disease?
Infective diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, lower abdominal pain and bleedings or cysts.
However, they often cause no pain or any other symptoms, thus remaining undetected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms reduce contraction risk, but they do not offer 100% protection.
This is because occasionally, the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted via smear infections and close bodily contact.
The first and most important experts recommend that people with frequent sexual partners undergo regular examinations.
If diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences are avoided.
